						               													<description>Zoondo B&amp;ocirc;plato consist of a real playing board (not a paper board) and 8 new &amp;quot;terrain&amp;quot; cards for Zoondo.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;There are 2 copies of each of the 4 types of terrain cards: Bananane, Dolwomen, Trempneu, and Glotrou.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Rules: Each player chooses 1 to 3 terrain cards from the face-down pile and places each one face-down on an open cell of the battlefield&amp;mdash;without looking at the card.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;During play, when a Zoon moves onto a cell with a terrain card, that player chooses one of the corners&amp;mdash;each card has two &amp;quot;success&amp;quot; and two &amp;quot;failure&amp;quot; corners. If an enemy Zoon already occupies the cell, nothing happens.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Bananane (associated with the Monkus):&amp;#10;&amp;#10;     Success: You can move your Zoon onto any cell adjacent to the Bananane&amp;#10;     Failure: Your opponent can move your Zoon onto any cell adjacent to the Bananane&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Dolwomen (associated with the Boarix):&amp;#10;&amp;#10;     Success: Your Zoon stops on the Dolwomen. As long as it remains on the Dolwomen, it gets +1 on its corners&amp;#10;     Failure: Your Zoon reverses course in front of the Dolwomen, similar to a fight ending in a draw (see rules: If your fight ends in a draw, your Zoon moves backward from the opponent one space in the direction from which it came)&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Trempneu (associated with the Rhinogoths):&amp;#10;&amp;#10;     Success: You can move your Zoon according to the grid shown on the Trempneu card&amp;#10;     Failure: Your Zoon stops on the Trempneu&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Glotrou (associated with the Warus):&amp;#10;&amp;#10;     Success: Nothing happens&amp;#10;     Failure: Your Zoon stops on the Glotrou and is flipped to its visible side. It can&amp;rsquo;t move and it fights with its visible side showing. You must use a complete move to flip your Zoon back to its hidden side&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
